FOR VERSION 0-0-0 USE ONLY
--

--- Version layout -- 
    a - b - c

a : major version, files with the same major version 
    always have the chance of being backwords 
    compatable (if they choose not to use new features)
b : minor version, files with the same minor version
    use the same number of flags in the header that do
    the same things. may change layout (but if so, a
    flag must be added to make the changes toggleable)
c : working version, changes here don't effect the
    layout of the file but do slightly effect how its
    interpreted.
     
------ Description -------

kr is used to determin where the player can and can't 
collide. while kr files are ment to be 1 file per map
multiple files can be loaded in if needed. however, its
not reccomended to. the data in a .kr file is meant to 
be read and edited in a text editor. before useage, 
please run the compile script to turn this into a .krcf
file.

this is version 0.0.0.

---- layout ----

the very first line, before ANY WHITESPACE, should be:

VERSION ( 0 , 0 ) ;

(this does not say crab)
here, replace A with the major version (0) and B with
the minor version (0). this makes sure the krcf 
compiler is in the right version. This is the version
declaration.

notice: the only whitespace supported in spaces. tabs
and newlines should not be used for formatting. however,
you can have multiple newlines in a row. tabs shouldn't
be an issue on a modern code editor though becouse they
usualy get reformated to spaces. spaces cannot be put
inbetween words, numbers, or anything else that seems
wrong. use semicolons, along with newlines, in order
to seperate different instructions.
any spaces used in the examples can be removed or
expanded.

notice: using a "#" anywhere will ignore anything that
comes after it on the same line, like a comment. these
will not get compiled and do not matter.

includeing the version declaration, the layout is as
follows:

1. version declaration
2. file information
3. data

---- file information ----

the information header comes after the version
declaration, and sets all the importent data needed for
the kr file to compile. each "equasion" is formated
as so:

NAME = VALUE ;

note that most things have defaults. if it has a
default, then it is not required to be set and the
default will be used instead.

-------------------------------------------------------
|   name   | value type | description                 |
|----------|------------|-----------------------------|
| USE_STLS |   bool     | if the variable is true,    |
|          |            | then .stl files can be      |
|          |            | loaded in with LOADFROM_STL |
|          |            | Default : false             |
-------------------------------------------------------

* yes, there is only one value here now but there might
  be more in the future

---- data ----

after the file information, you will need to put a line
of data to let the compiler know it is now reading data

this is formated as so:

COLLISION_DATA :

note: nothing comes after the colon (exept for spaces)
maybe. and also a newline, you need a newline after the
colon.

then, for each shape you want to use you write its type
first. this can either be defined with --TYPE to use a
named type of >>type to use a ID type (uint). you can't
have both. Insted of a semicolon, use brackets.
everything else in the shape declaration will occur
within thease brackets. see:

-- TYPE { }
>> type { }

next, on a newline is the position and rotation. use:

POS = { valuex , valuey , valuez } ;
ROT = { valuex , valuey , valuez } ;

where valuex, valuey, and valuez are replaced wiht the
x, y and z rotation and position. these cannot be 
split into a newline. 

NOTICE: shape TRIANGLE or ID 0 will NOT use rot,
insted skipping directly to the paramiters. (however,
pos will still be used)

next, on a newline, is the paramiters. starting the
list of paramiters is indicated by "PARAMITERS = {" 
a matching "}" is expected when the list of paramiters
finish. inbetween the parentices are a list of the 
paramiters used, exept position and rotation. formated
like so:

PARAMITERS = {
    PARAMITER : VALUE ,
    PARAMITER : VALUE
} ;

each new paramiter must be on a new line, will be
seperated with a comma, and the opening PARAMITERS = {
must have a newline directly after it (or a few spaces
after it) and the matching } must be on a new line and
cannot have anthing after it like the opening one.

that defines one shape. alltogether, the total shape
definition looks like:

--TYPE  {
    POS = { valuex , valuey , valuez } ;
    ROT = { valuex , valuey , valuez } ;
    PARAMITERS = {
        PARAMITER : VALUE ,
        PARAMITER : VALUE 
    } ;
}
a note about paramiters: while in the shape tables, 
their names are lowercase, in the file the must be all
upercase.

the next shape definition can be on the next line after
that, or the end of the file.

HOWEVER, another way to put data in is by useing 
LOADFROM_STL. this does not require useing --type, pos,
rot, and paramiters. in fact, they are prohibited.
useing LOADFROM_STL insted of a shape definition can
look like:

LOADFROM_STL( "filename" ) ;

as a note: LOADFROM_STL will ONLY use triangles. this,
while convient, is ineffecent so its reccomended to 
use a normal shape definition as it can be quicker.

also, you must replace filename with the name of the
file you want to load from. it must be in quotes and it
must be the exact filename, no extra spaces, newlines,
and absolutely no quotation marks. if the file has 
quotes in its name, rename the file.



